 align=left|[[Eline Berings]] || align=left|{{BEL}} || 8.14 || \n|-\n| 17 || 2 || 2 || align=left|[[Gr\u00e9ta Kerekes]] || align=left|{{HUN}} || 8.17 || \n|-\n| 18 || 2 || 8 || align=left|[[Nooralotta Neziri]] || align=left|{{FIN}} || 8.20 || \n|-\n| 19 || 3 || 2 || align=left|[[Reetta Hurske]] || align=left|{{FIN}} || 8.20 || \n|-\n| 20 || 1 || 1 || align=left|[[Ivana Lon\u010darek]] || align=left|{{CRO}} || 8.21 || \n|-\n| 21 || 3 || 7 || align=left|[[Karolina Ko\u0142eczek]] || align=left|{{POL}} || 8.21 || \n|-\n| 22 || 1 || 2 || align=left|[[Michelle Jenneke]] || align=left|{{AUS}} || 8.22 || \n|-\n| 23 || 1 || 8 || align=left|[[Luca Koz\u00e1k]] || align=left|{{HUN}} || 8.24 || \n|-\n| 24 || 2 || 7 || align=left|[[Eefje Boons]] || align=left|{{NED}} || 8.24 || \n|}\n\n===Final===\n[[File:Kendra Harrison Birmingham 2018.jpg|thumb|350px|The finish of the race]]\nThe final was started on 3 March at 20:55.<ref>[https://media.aws.iaaf.org/competitiondocuments/pdf/6019/AT-60H-W-f----.RS6.pdf Final results]</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Rank !! Lane !! Name !! Nationality !! Time !! Notes\n|-\n| {{gold1}} || 5 || align=left|[[Kendra Harrison]] || align=left|{{USA}} || 7.70 || '''{{AthAbbr|CR|IAAF World Indoor Championships}}'''\n|-\n| {{silver2}} || 6 || align=left|[[Christina Manning]] || align=left|{{USA}} || 7.79 || \n|-\n| {{bronze3}} || 4 || align=left|[[Nadine Visser]] || align=left|{{NED}} || 7.84 ||  \n|-\n| 4 || 3 || align=left|[[Sharika Nelvis]] || align=left|{{USA}} || 7.86 || \n|-\n| 5 || 7 || align=left|[[Cindy Roleder]] || align=left|{{GER}} || 7.87 || \n|-\n| 6 || 2 || align=left|[[Isabelle Pedersen]] || align=left|{{NOR}} || 7.94 || \n|-\n| 7 || 1 || align=left|[[Oluwatobiloba Amusan]] || align=left|{{NGR}} || 8.05 || \n|-\n| 8 || 8 || align=left|[[Devynne Charlton]] || align=left|{{BAH}} || 8.18 ||  \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{external media|video=1={{youtube|AqJjeyxf3mM|Women's 60m hurdles: World Indoor Championships Birmingham 2018}}}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{WIC60mHurdles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2018 Iaaf World Indoor Championships - Women's 60 Metres Hurdles}}\n[[Category:2018 IAAF World Indoor Championships|60 metres hurdles]]\n[[Category:60 metres hurdles at the World Athletics Indoor Championships]]\n[[Category:2018 in women's athletics]]\n", "name_user": "Games of the world", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2018_IAAF_World_Indoor_Championships_%E2%80%93_Women%27s_60_metres_hurdles"}
{"title_page": "Forlorn hope", "text_new": "{{about||the community formerly with this name|Hopeton, California|the 1865 voyage of an open boat along the Western Australian coast |Forlorn Hope (boat)}}\n[[File:Forlorn hope.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Colin Campbell, 1st Baron Clyde|Colin Campbell]] leading the 'forlorn hope' at the [[Siege of San Sebasti\u00e1n]], 1813. Painting by [[William Barnes Wollen]]]]\n{{Wiktionary}}\nA '''forlorn hope''' is a band of soldiers or other combatants chosen to take the [[vanguard|leading part]] in a military operation, such as a [[Suicide mission|suicidal assault]] through the [[kill zone]] of a defended position, where the risk of casualties is high.<ref name = \"brit\">{{cite EB1911|wstitle=Forlorn Hope}}</ref>\n\nSuch a band is also known as the ''enfants perdus'' (lit. \"Lost Children\").<ref>[http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/enfants%20perdus \"enfants perdus\"], ''Merriam-Webster Dictionary''</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe term comes from the [[Dutch language|Dutch]] ''verloren hoop'', literally \"lost <!-- Please read the article, and the references, then you will see why this shouldn't be changed to \"lost hope\"! -->troop\".<!-- Please read the article, and the references, then you will see why this shouldn't be changed to \"lost hope\" every couple of weeks! --> The term was used in military contexts to denote a troop formation.<ref>''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'': \"forlorn hope\"</ref><ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Kilian\n  | first = Cornelius\n  | authorlink = :nl:Cornelius Kiliaan\n  | title = Etymologicum Teutonic\u00e6 Lingu\u00e6\n  | publisher = [[Jan Moretus]] (cited in Oxford English Dictionary)\n  | year = 1593\n  | location = Antwerp\n  | pages =\n  | url =\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | isbn = }}</ref><ref>[http://mw1.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/forlorn_hope ''Merriam Webster'' entry: \"forlorn hope\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011105401/http://mw1.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/forlorn_hope |date=2007-10-11 }}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Dutch word ''hoop'' (in its sense of \"heap\" in English) is not [[cognate]] with English \"hope\": this is an example of [[folk etymology]].<ref>{{cite book |last       = Newman\n |first      = John B\n |authorlink = \n |editor     = Raphael, Lawrence J\n |editor2    = Raphael, Carolyn B\n |editor3    = Valdodinos, Miriam R\n |title      = Language and Cognition: Essays in Honor of Arthur J. Bronstein\n |publisher  = Plenum Press\n |year       = 1984\n |location   = New York\n |url        = https://archive.org/details/languagecognitio0000unse/page/203\n |doi        = \n |id         = \n |isbn       = 0-306-41433-3\n |pages      = [https://archive.org/details/languagecognitio0000unse/page/203 203\u20134]\n}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Todd\n  | first = Loreto\n  | authorlink =\n  |author2=Hancock, Ian |authorlink2=Ian F. Hancock\n  | title = International English Usage\n  | publisher = Routledge\n  | year = 1990\n  | location = London\n  | url =\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | isbn =0-415-05102-9\n  | page = 233 }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Attridge\n  | first = Derek\n  | authorlink =\n  | title = Peculiar Language: Literature as Difference from the Renaissance to James Joyce\n  | publisher = Cornell University Press\n  | year = 1988\n  | location = Ithaca, New York\n  | url =https://archive.org/details/peculiarlanguage00attr\n  | url-access = registration\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | isbn = 0-415-34057-8\n  | page = [https://archive.org/details/peculiarlanguage00attr/page/112 112]\n  | quote=the Dutch phrase ''verloren hoop'', the \"lost heap\"\u2026became naturalized\u2014and generalized\u2014as ''forlorn hope''...a quaint misunderstanding [from] folk etymology. }}</ref> The mistranslation of ''verloren hoop'' as \"forlorn hope\" is \"a quaint misunderstanding\" using the nearest-sounding English words.<ref>{{cite web|title=The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language |publisher=[[Bartleby.com|Bartleby]] |year=2000 |url=http://www.bartleby.com/61/33/F0263300.html |accessdate=18 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090306005906/http://www.bartleby.com/61/33/F0263300.html |archivedate=March 6, 2009 }}</ref> This false etymology has been strengthened by the fact that in Dutch, the word ''hoop'' is a [[homograph]] meaning \"hope\" as well as \"heap\", though the two senses have different etymologies.\n\n==History==\nIn the German [[mercenary]] armies of the ''[[Landsknecht]]s'', these troops were called the ''Verlorene Haufen'', which has the same meaning as the Dutch term, the word ''[[Haufen]]'' itself being a general term for a loosely organised group of men. These men carried [[zweih\u00e4nder|long double-handed swords]], with which they had to hew their way through the massive pike formations opposing them. They also had to withstand the first wave of attacks when defending a [[Breastwork (fortification)|breastwork]]. Members of the ''Verlorene Haufen'' earned double pay, thus giving them the name of ''[[Doppels\u00f6ldner]]'' ('Double-wagers'). Since there were not enough volunteers for this assignment, criminals who had been sentenced to death were taken into the ranks as well. As a field sign, the ''Verlorene Haufen'' carried a red ''Blutfahne'' ('Blood Banner').\n\nBy extension, the term ''forlorn hope'' became used for any body of troops placed in a hazardous position, ''e.g.'', an exposed outpost, or the defenders of an [[outwork]] in advance of the main defensive position.<ref name=\"brit\" /> This usage was especially common in accounts of the [[English Civil War]], as well as in the [[British Army]] in the [[Peninsular War]] of 1808\u20131814. In the days of muzzle-loading [[musket]]s, the term was most frequently used to refer to the first wave of soldiers attacking a breach in defenses during a [[siege]].\n\nWhile it was likely that most members of the forlorn hope would be killed or wounded, the intention was that some would survive long enough to seize a foothold that could be reinforced, or, at least, that a second wave with better prospects could be sent in while the defenders were reloading or engaged in mopping up the remnants of the first wave.<ref name=\"brit\" />  That said, such soldiers were rarely suicidal or foolhardy: British troops of the forlorn hope at the 1812 [[Siege of Badajoz (1812)|Siege of Badajoz]] carried a large bag ({{convert|5|-|6|ft}} by {{convert|2|ft}} in diameter) stuffed with hay or straw, which was thrown down into the enemy trenches to create a cushion and prevent injury as they jumped down.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/united-states/2018/08/11/never-trump-republicans-could-have-their-revenge|title='Never Trump' Republicans could have their revenge|last=|first=|date=9 August 2018|work=The Economist|access-date=15 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The London Journal, and Weekly Record of Literature, Science, and Art|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XRRLAQAAMAAJ|year=1847|publisher=G. Vickers|page=155}}</ref>\n\nA forlorn hope may have been composed of volunteers and conscripted criminals, and were frequently led by ambitious junior officers with hopes of personal advancement: if the volunteers survived, and performed courageously, they would be expected to benefit in the form of promotions, cash gifts, and added glory to their name (a military tradition at least as old as the Roman Republic.<ref>Crowns were bestowed after a Roman triumph by generals to soldiers who won personal victories in battle... [such as being] first to scale a wall. [[Cassius Dio|Dio Cassius]]: Roman History 6.21\n</ref>) The commanding officer was virtually guaranteed both a promotion and a long-term boost to his career prospects if he survived.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Army of the French Revolution: From Citizen-soldier to Instrument of Power|last=Bertaud |first=Jean-Paul|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=1988|isbn=|location=|pages=23\u201337|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn consequence, despite the grave risks involved for all concerned, there was often serious competition for the opportunity to lead such an assault and to display conspicuous valor.\n\nThe French equivalent of the forlorn hope, called ''Les Enfants Perdus'' ('The Lost Children'), were all guaranteed promotion to officer rank should they survive. Both enlisted men and officers joined the dangerous mission as an opportunity to raise themselves in the army.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Banzai charge]]\n* [[Battle of Sari Bair]]\n* [[Second Battle of Fort Wagner]]\n* [[Cannon fodder]]\n* [[Frontal assault]]\n* [[Inghimasi]]\n* [[Kamikaze]]\n* [[Penal military unit]]\n* [[Shock troops]]\n* [[Suicide attack]]\n* [[Suicide mission]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Military slang and jargon]]\n[[Category:Siege tactics]]\n", "text_old": "{{for2|the community formerly with this name|[[Hopeton, California]]| the 1865 voyage of an open boat along the Western Australian coast |[[Forlorn Hope (boat)]]}}\n[[File:Forlorn hope.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Colin Campbell, 1st Baron Clyde|Colin Campbell]] leading the 'forlorn hope' at the [[Siege of San Sebasti\u00e1n]], 1813. Painting by [[William Barnes Wollen]]]]\n{{Wiktionary}}\nA '''forlorn hope''' is a band of soldiers or other combatants chosen to take the [[vanguard|leading part]] in a military operation, such as a [[Suicide mission|suicidal assault]] through the [[kill zone]] of a defended position, where the risk of casualties is high.<ref name = \"brit\">{{cite EB1911|wstitle=Forlorn Hope}}</ref>\n\nSuch a band is also known as the ''enfants perdus'' (lit. \"Lost Children\").<ref>[http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/enfants%20perdus \"enfants perdus\"], ''Merriam-Webster Dictionary''</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe term comes from the [[Dutch language|Dutch]] ''verloren hoop'', literally \"lost <!-- Please read the article, and the references, then you will see why this shouldn't be changed to \"lost hope\"! -->troop\".<!-- Please read the article, and the references, then you will see why this shouldn't be changed to \"lost hope\" every couple of weeks! --> The term was used in military contexts to denote a troop formation.<ref>''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'': \"forlorn hope\"</ref><ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Kilian\n  | first = Cornelius\n  | authorlink = :nl:Cornelius Kiliaan\n  | title = Etymologicum Teutonic\u00e6 Lingu\u00e6\n  | publisher = [[Jan Moretus]] (cited in Oxford English Dictionary)\n  | year = 1593\n  | location = Antwerp\n  | pages =\n  | url =\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | isbn = }}</ref><ref>[http://mw1.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/forlorn_hope ''Merriam Webster'' entry: \"forlorn hope\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011105401/http://mw1.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/forlorn_hope |date=2007-10-11 }}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Dutch word ''hoop'' (in its sense of \"heap\" in English) is not [[cognate]] with English \"hope\": this is an example of [[folk etymology]].<ref>{{cite book |last       = Newman\n |first      = John B\n |authorlink = \n |editor     = Raphael, Lawrence J\n |editor2    = Raphael, Carolyn B\n |editor3    = Valdodinos, Miriam R\n |title      = Language and Cognition: Essays in Honor of Arthur J. Bronstein\n |publisher  = Plenum Press\n |year       = 1984\n |location   = New York\n |url        = https://archive.org/details/languagecognitio0000unse/page/203\n |doi        = \n |id         = \n |isbn       = 0-306-41433-3\n |pages      = [https://archive.org/details/languagecognitio0000unse/page/203 203\u20134]\n}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Todd\n  | first = Loreto\n  | authorlink =\n  |author2=Hancock, Ian |authorlink2=Ian F. Hancock\n  | title = International English Usage\n  | publisher = Routledge\n  | year = 1990\n  | location = London\n  | url =\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | isbn =0-415-05102-9\n  | page = 233 }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Att